photos.description: "In keeping with his leadership role in the creation of the Shorewood neighborhood and the development of the Doe Bay Water Users Association, Helge Johanson has assumed the guide of a Keystone Cop. Here he is determined not to let any traffic through until this new Shorewood neighborhood road is properly dedicated."
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook (Photo Courtesy of Margaret Fickel family)

photos.people: Carrol Culver (from the back), Don Leatherwood, Thurman Bond, John Keel, Joe Bond, Marian Barbee and Bill Keel.
photos.description: "This photograph shows the Doe Bay Fire Hall under construction in 1970. Bill Trogdon was the pro bono architect. Logs were donated by community members and milled free of charge by the Bond Lumber Company. Pictured are the stalwart leaders of the all-volunteer labor force; from the left: Carrol Culver (from the back), Don Leatherwood, Thurman Bond, John Keel, Joe Bond, Marian Barbee and Bill Keel."
photos.source: "Doe Bay History and Recipes" Cookbook (Photo Courtesy Thurman Bond)

Double exposure.  Something that happened frequently with film cameras.  You never really knew until after the film was sent away to be developed.  (Ken)

Cabin 12 clearly visible (built in 1950).  Floats still up on beach which were usually launched and set in place in mid to late May.  Note how thin the trees were on the bluff property which had been recently logged.  Scars from the log dump at far end of beach still visible.  (Ken)

A luxury yacht named "Southern Seas" anchored in the bay at Pt. Lawrence Lodge.  I rowed out to see if anyone wanted to go ashore and got a couple of passengers including the "captain". He gave me a 5$ bill for my troubles - I was rich!  (Ken)

The infamous 'Herring Barge" that came from Seattle to catch live herring.  Each night after dark they put out large floodlights and a herring seine net.  The herring schooled under the light and were then hearded through opening side doors on the barge into live tanks that kept them alive with pumps.  Over the course of many trips they caught thousands of herring, before it was outlawed by the State.  I would row out and go aboard to watch the operation.  (Ken)
